Why did you use inheritance?
  I used inheritance because it help classes share common features and behaviors. 

Why did you use interfaces?
  I used interfaces to represent actions or abilities that an object can perform. 

Can Helicopter inherit from both Vehicle and Airplane? Why or why not?
  No, a Helicopter cannot inherit from both Vehicle and Airplane in C# because C# only allows a class to inherit from one parent class. This rule helps avoid confusion and conflicts that may occur if both parent classes contain similar methods or properties.

Why can Helicopter implement both IFlyable and IDriveable?
  A Helicopter can implement both IFlyable and IDriveable because C# allows a class to implement multiple interfaces. Since interfaces only define behaviors and do not provide full implementations, there is no conflict in having a class support more than one ability.

If a Submarine can both sail and dive, how would you design it?
  I would design a Submarine by making it inherit from a Vehicle class and implement both ISailable and IDiveable interfaces. This approach shows that a Submarine is a type of Vehicle while also having the abilities to sail on the surface and dive underwater, making the design simple, flexible, and easy to expand.
